observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to ensure the following:
The Municipal Treasurer liquidate his cash advance soonest amounting to ₱1,476,300 for proper recording in the books of accounts;
Strict enforcement of the “No liquidation, No cash advance” rule by requiring the Municipal Accountant’s Certification that previous cash advance has been liquidated and accounted for in the books before another CA is granted to the same accountable officer;
Prompt liquidation of cash advances; and
Refrain from granting cash advances near yearend when the possibility of payment to grantees are remote, so that no cash advances remain unliquidated at yearend.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to ensure the following:

The	Inventory Committee of the Municipality		be created to take charge in the physical count of inventories;

The physical count of inventories	be conducted by the Inventory Committee semestrally and that the Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) is prepared and submitted to the Accounting Office and the Audit Team;

c)	The Accounting Office reconcile	the	 RPCI with their accounting records and draw the appropriate adjustments	for		any discrepancies		noted after		proper
verification.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to ensure that:

The Municipal Engineer furnish the Municipal Accountant with the SWAs of the projects listed in Table 1 including the on-going Municipal Water System Construction, and the duly signed Payroll to support the reimbursement of ₱8,000.00 in Table 2;
The payment for wages of laborers through reimbursements be stopped;
The Municipal Accountant reclassify the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts of the completed projects based on the SWA submitted by the Municipal Engineering Office and provide for the corresponding depreciation; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Engineer prepare and submit the SWA for all projects as supporting documents for final payment, whichever mode of procurement is used.

We recommended and management agreed to: 

Require the Municipal Engineering Office to find ways to fast track the implementation of the remaining infrastructure projects;

Hire a reasonable number of qualified engineers to help in the preparation of plans and program of works and in project monitoring;

Ensure the validation and settlement of the right of way of proposed projects before inclusion in the AIP; and 

Consider funding significant projects and re-evaluate the unimplemented projects considering the rising cost of construction materials.

We have recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:

draw the appropriate adjusting entries to reclassify and correct the depreciation of  the affected PPE accounts:

segregate the cost of the local road networks, maintain separate SLs for the road sub-components, determine the appropriate estimated useful life and compute the depreciation of each sub-components;

determine the composition of the road networks amounting to ₱785,757.07 that remain unidentified;

ensure that the estimated useful life of the PPE assets complies with Section 262(e), 
GAM for LGUs;   

exclude the infrastructure assets from the provision of residual value pursuant to  Section 262(h) of the GAM for LGUs and Section IV(14) of COA Circular 2015-008; and



determine the useful life of the Other Land Improvements account and compute the corresponding depreciation.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 

determine  and   trace  the source or cause of the prior year’s unreconciled amount of  P3,422,925.93  in the subsidiary ledger; 

review the subsidiary ledger of the “Other Payables” account and the  other subsidiary ledger items of the “Due to NGAs” to establish their correct balances.

1.6  We have recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
draw the appropriate adjusting entries to reclassify and correct the depreciation of  the affected PPE accounts:
segregate the cost of the local road networks, maintain separate SLs for the road sub-components, determine the appropriate estimated useful life and compute the depreciation of each sub-components;
determine the composition of the road networks amounting to ₱785,757.07 that remain unidentified;
ensure that the estimated useful life of the PPE assets complies with Section 262(e), GAM for LGUs;
exclude the infrastructure assets from the provision of residual value pursuant to  Section 262(h) of GAM for LGUs and Section IV(14) of COA Circular 2015-008; and
determine the useful life of the Other Land Improvements account and compute the corresponding depreciation

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 

a. determine  and   trace  the source or cause of the prior year’s unreconciled amount of  P3,422,925.93  in the subsidiary ledger; 



b. identify    the    proper subsidiary items for the road projects under CHARMP and Assistance to Municipalities amounting to  P427,662.48 and P5,340,252.62, respectively; 

c. review the subsidiary ledger of the “Other Payables” account and the  other subsidiary ledger items of the “Due to NGAs” to establish their correct balances; and 

d. effect    the    necessary adjustments for any reconciling items noted in order to correct the balances of the individual accounts in the subsidiary ledgers.

2.6. We have recommended and Management agreed to instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
a. Determine the details of the variance amounting to Php2,647,452.84;
b. Effect immediately the necessary adjustments to bring the balances into agreement;
c. Henceforth, record transactions simultaneously to the receivable and payable accounts; and
d. Perform periodic reconciliation of the Due From/To Other Funds accounts.
